    <div class="section">
      <h2>Detailed Benefits of Preparation Enabled by Early Warnings</h2>
      <h3>Loss of Life Reduction</h3>
      <p>Early alerts allow communities to evacuate vulnerable groups (elderly, children) and position first responders nearby. For example, in the 2004 Indian Ocean tsunami, a 30-minute warning could have saved 100,000+ lives. Faster distribution of pre-positioned recovery supplies (stored in safe zones) enables quicker medical aid, reducing secondary deaths from injury or exposure.</p>

      <h3>Environmental & Economic Savings</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><span class="highlight">Pre-Positioning Supplies</span>: Supplies placed short distances from potential impact areas allow rapid deployment, minimizing environmental damage from delayed cleanup (e.g., preventing pollution spread).</li>
        <li><span class="highlight">Faster First Responders</span>: Pre-deployed teams reduce response time, limiting fire spread, flood expansion, or contamination — saving billions in long-term ecosystem restoration.</li>
        <li><span class="highlight">Overall Cost Savings</span>: Every $1 invested in preparedness saves $13 in damages (UNDRR). Global disasters cost $224 billion in 2025; early warnings could cut 20–50% ($45–112 billion saved annually).</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <h2>Conclusion: Investing in Early Warning for a Resilient Future</h2>
      <p>Advanced early warning systems enable proactive preparation — evacuation, resource positioning, and faster response — dramatically reducing human, environmental, and economic losses. The cost of such technology is a small investment compared to a single disaster's toll — it pays for itself many times over by preventing or minimizing damage and enabling quicker recovery.</p>
